Solid priorities for fragile states
LONDON/MONROVIA/KIGALI – No country has been spared the repercussions of the COVID-19 pandemic.
However, the most "fragile" states in the world face a set of particularly complex issues.
Indeed, before the pandemic began, Yemen, Sudan, Haiti, Sierra Leone, Myanmar, Afghanistan, Venezuela, and other countries were already grappling with poverty, conflicts, corruption, and inadequate public administration.
Today, these elements leave these countries unprepared to manage the COVID-19 crisis.
What each country needs to get through the pandemic is precisely what fragile states lack: an effective state apparatus capable of designing and implementing an action plan, an efficient police force to enforce rules, social programs that provide funds and services, as well as healthcare supplies and services to treat infected individuals.
The immediate lack of state resources is felt in the field of public health.
While Europe has 4,000 intensive care beds per million inhabitants, several regions in Africa have only five per million inhabitants.
Mali has only three fans for the entire country.   (Note: In this context, "ventilateurs" likely refers to "fans" as in appliances used for cooling, rather than air traffic control or any other meaning of the word "ventilateur.")
An effective response also involves confidence in the state's intervention.
However, in addition to its lack of resources, the public administration in most fragile states does not fare much better in terms of gaining the population's approval.
In countries that are recovering from a conflict or suffering from endemic corruption, several people will refrain from supporting the government even if it turns out to be capable of governing.
A strong private sector is also an essential component of effective and solid states.
Citizens should be able to work to support their families, and the state should be able to collect tax revenues to assist those who cannot.
However, in fragile states, the official economy is not sufficiently present to meet these needs.
Earlier in the crisis, there was hope that some fragile states could avoid the worst health consequences of COVID-19 due to their youthful demographic weight and geographical remoteness.
However, from our perspective as co-presidents of the new Council on State Fragility, it must be admitted that this was not the case.
In recent weeks, Sudan, South Sudan, Somalia, and Yemen have all experienced infection and mortality rates rivaling those of developed countries hit hardest by the coronavirus.
Worse still, the economic consequences of the pandemic are likely to be even more significant for fragile states. These will not be solely the result of national lockdowns, but also of what is happening abroad.
Trade with countries like China has declined, remittances from overseas workers have fallen, prices of basic goods and oil revenues have collapsed, and deficits are accumulating.
Since fragile states rely on imports for the majority of their food, there is increasing talk of "hunger" and even of "famine".
We should now understand that the problems of less prosperous countries become, for the most part, global problems whether in the form of massive migrations, criminal or terrorist organizations, or economic repercussions.
Given that half of the impoverished populations will be living in fragile states by 2030, these problems will continue to worsen.
That is why the Council on State Fragility has made it an absolute priority to draw attention to the specific challenges that these countries must overcome.
The council, composed of former global leaders, ministers, diplomats, business personalities, academics, and development organization presidents, will combine cutting-edge research with meticulous political knowledge. Its goal will be to guide national and international policymakers who will determine how fragile states emerge from this crisis and address their broader and deeper issues.
Decentralization, adaptability, and the thoughtful use of data will be essentials.
For example, it is widely proven that "targeted confinement" of local outbreaks is often more appropriate than national confinement.
Such knowledge could prove crucial for fragile states.
However, we must act quickly before the critical phase of the pandemic in the Western world comes to an end and the sense of urgency fades away.
We propose five recommendations.
Firstly, access to social protection must be simpler and faster.
Sometimes, this will be synonymous with universal eligibility rather than precise targeting.
Mobile telephone networks should be leveraged to gather information on immediate needs and to disburse small regular payments (although of limited duration).
Secondly, national food production should be encouraged.
For example, Sierra Leone, which cultivated rice, has become increasingly dependent in recent decades.
In general, Africa accounts for 60% of the world's unused arable land.
The local production initiatives for staple crops must be rapidly scaled up to a much greater extent.
Thirdly, as soon as vaccine production is launched, the international community must ensure that fragile states are not excluded from the market by wealthier countries.
When the threat is a contagious pathogen, no country is safe unless all are safe.
We must advocate for and accelerate the production of multiple vaccines to ensure rapid and widespread distribution.
Fourthly, enterprises in fragile states need immediate assistance.
As noted by the financial institutions most involved in international development; small enterprises in less affluent countries are often neglected and suffer the adverse consequences of broader goals and rules (since it is easier to achieve a goal by investing in larger-scale projects in bigger economies).
However, it is precisely these small businesses that need larger investments.
Finally, the G20 should do more to support heavily indebted fragile states that are forced to choose between paying their foreign creditors or saving their population.
It is planned that countries receiving bilateral development aid must repay approximately 40 billion dollars to private and public creditors this year alone.
To prevent this financial shock, we urge all members of the G20 to suspend accumulated debts not only until next year, but also until the end of the crisis.
Moreover, it is essential that all fragile states obtain emergency financing to support their efforts to contain COVID-19 and mitigate its economic impacts—especially countries that do not typically have access to the financing of the World Bank or the International Monetary Fund.
The COVID-19 pandemic will exacerbate existing problems in all fragile states around the world.
However, if the international community reacts promptly, we can mitigate the worst consequences of the pandemic.
If there is one lesson to be learned from this crisis, it is that livelihoods and lives will be saved if we move faster than the virus.
